This is mainly because the runtime jars here is different from the compile time jars.

That is :

1. compile the source code with denpendency jars version 1 and produce app;
2. run the app with runtime dependency jars version 2;

version 1 and version 2 are different, so there occurs the error.

Found some workaround to fix this issue. One Pair serializer and one deserializer need to be defined and used in the object mapper.

```Java
public final class PairSerializer extends JsonSerializer&lt;Pair&gt; {

    @Override
    public void serialize(Pair value, JsonGenerator gen, SerializerProvider serializers) throws IOException {
        gen.writeStartObject();
        gen.writeObjectField(&quot;left&quot;, value.getLeft());
        gen.writeObjectField(&quot;right&quot;, value.getRight());
        gen.writeEndObject();
    }
}
```
```Java
public final class PairDeserializer extends JsonDeserializer&lt;Pair&gt; {

    @Override
    public Pair deserialize(JsonParser p, DeserializationContext ctxt) throws IOException {
        p.nextValue();
        Integer key= p.getValueAsInt();
        p.nextToken();
        p.nextToken();
        Integer value= p.getValueAsInt();
        p.nextToken();
        return MutablePair.of(key, value);
    }
}
```
These two need to be added in the `OM` definition
```Java
OBJECT_MAPPER.registerModule(new SimpleModule().addSerializer(Pair.class, new PairSerializer()));
OBJECT_MAPPER.registerModule(new SimpleModule().addDeserializer(Pair.class, new PairDeserializer()));
```

It&#39;s easier to use custom defined POJO classes instead of using library structures, in case you have the flexibility.

